To generate a table of contents (TOC) automatically in a LaTeX document, you can use the `\tableofcontents` command. This command will create a table of contents using the sectioning commands (e.g. `\chapter`, `\section`, `\subsection`, etc.) that have been used in the document.

Here is an example of how you can include a table of contents in a LaTeX document:

```
\documentclass{book}

% This command is used to include packages that provide additional functionality
\usepackage{lipsum} % This package generates filler text

\begin{document}

% This command generates the table of contents
\tableofcontents

% Now we can start writing the content of the document

\chapter{Introduction}
\lipsum[1-20] % This command generates 20 paragraphs of filler text

\section{Background}
\lipsum[21-40]

\subsection{Related Work}
\lipsum[41-50]

\chapter{Methods}
\lipsum[51-70]

\section{Experiment Setup}
\lipsum[71-80]

\subsection{Data Collection}
\lipsum[81-90]

\section{Data Analysis}
\lipsum[91-100]

\chapter{Conclusion}
\lipsum[101-120]

\end{document}
```

In this example, the `\tableofcontents` command is placed right after the `\begin{document}` command. This will generate a table of contents using the `\chapter`, `\section`, and `\subsection` commands that are used later in the document.

To generate the TOC, LaTeX needs to know the structure of the document beforehand, so it is important that the `\tableofcontents` command appears before the sectioning commands.

When you compile this LaTeX document, it will generate a table of contents with the correct page numbers for each section. Note that the page numbers in the TOC may change as you add or remove content from your document.

You can also use the `\addcontentsline` command to manually add entries to the TOC. For example, you can use the following command to add an entry for a figure:

```
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{My Figure}
\begin{figure}
  \includegraphics{my_figure}
  \caption{This is my figure}
\end{figure}
```

This will add an entry for the figure to the TOC, under the "Section" heading. You can change the heading by replacing "section" with "chapter", "subsection", etc.

